SENATE BILL 842
P1, P4, P2 6lr2046
CF HB 1147
By: Senator Feldman
Introduced and read first time: February 6, 2026
Assigned to: Education, Energy, and the Environment
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Public Service Commission – Administrative Operations and Personnel Matters
3 (Public Service Commission Flexibility Act)
4 FOR the purpose of establishing that the exercise by the Public Service Commission of its
5 authority is an essential government function; altering the duties of the Commission
6 and the Executive Secretary of the Commission; providing for the designation of a
7 certain employee as Deputy Executive Secretary of the Commission; requiring the
8 Commission to submit certain information to the Department of Budget and
9 Management each year, keep certain records, and submit to certain audits;
10 authorizing the Commission to employ or retain as independent contractors certain
11 consultants and experts; requiring the Commission to establish a personnel
12 management system that operates independently of the State Personnel
13 Management System; altering the application of certain provisions of the State
14 Personnel and Pensions Article to Commission employees; requiring that all
15 employee compensation be determined by the Commission; requiring that certain
16 employees of the Commission be considered as permanent State employees, receive
17 certain credit for service, and be granted certain compensation consideration for
18 certain purposes; repealing provisions related to certain salary plan changes and
19 reporting requirements for certain personnel matters; exempting the Commission
20 from certain taxes and certain provisions of State procurement law; requiring that
21 certain employees of the Commission remain in the State Personnel Management
22 System until the Commission adopts an independent personnel management
23 system; and generally relating to the administration and powers of the Public Service
24 Commission.
25 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
26 Article – Public Utilities
27 Section 2–101, 2–104, and 2–108
28 Annotated Code of Maryland
29 (2025 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
