6 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
7 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
8 Article – Public Utilities
9 2–101.
10 (a) There is a Public Service Commission.
11 (b) The Commission is an independent unit in the Executive Branch of State
12 government.
13 (c) THE EXERCISE BY THE COMMISSION OF ITS AUTHORITY UNDER THIS
14 DIVISION IS AN ESSENTIAL GOVERNMENT FUNCTION.
15 (D) The Commission:
16 (1) shall carry out the functions assigned to it by law; AND
17 (2) MAY TAKE ACTIONS NECESSARY TO IMPLEMENT THE PROVISIONS
18 OF LAW UNDER ITS JURISDICTION.
19 2–104.
20 (a) The Commission shall appoint an Executive Secretary.
21 (b) The Executive Secretary serves at the pleasure of the Commission.
22 (c) The Executive Secretary shall:
23 (1) keep the records of the Commission, including a record of proceedings,
24 all documents required to be filed with the Commission, all orders, regulations, and
25 decisions of the Commission, and all dockets and files;
26 (2) certify true copies of those materials;
27 (3) designate an employee of the Commission to SERVE AS THE DEPUTY
28 EXECUTIVE SECRETARY WHO SHALL perform the duties of Executive Secretary when
29 the Executive Secretary is absent; [and]

SENATE BILL 842 3
1 (4) DIRECT AND SUPERVISE THE ADMINISTRATIVE AFFAIRS AND
2 ACTIVITIES OF THE COMMISSION IN ACCORDANCE WITH ITS REGULATIONS AND
3 POLICIES;
4 (5) APPROVE ALL ACCOUNTS FOR SALARIES, PER DIEM PAYMENTS,
5 AND ALL ALLOWABLE EXPENSES OF THE COMMISSION, ITS EMPLOYEES, AND ITS
6 CONSULTANTS;
7 (6) APPROVE ALL EXPENSES INCIDENTAL TO OPERATING THE
8 COMMISSION; AND
9 [(4)] (7) perform the other duties that the Commission prescribes.
10 (d) With the approval of the Commission and in conformity with Title 10, Subtitle
11 6, Part III of the State Government Article, the Executive Secretary may destroy any record
12 or document that the Commission possesses, including a record or document required by
13 law to be filed with the Commission, if:
14 (1) the record or document has been on file for at least 3 years; and
15 (2) the Executive Secretary considers the document to be obsolete.
16 2–108.
17 (a) (1) The principal office of the Commission shall be in Baltimore City at the
18 place that the Commission selects.
19 (2) Except for legal holidays, the offices of the Commission shall be open
20 for business during regular business hours from Monday through Friday and at other times
21 as the Commission considers necessary.
22 (b) (1) The Commission shall meet at the times and places in the State as the
23 Commission considers necessary.
24 (2) For purposes of the Open Meetings Act, a project site visit or
25 educational field tour may not be considered a meeting of the Commission if no
26 organizational business is conducted.
27 (c) The Commission shall have a seal.
28 (d) (1) (I) The State budget shall provide sufficient money for the
29 Commission to hire, develop, and organize a staff to perform the functions of the
30 Commission, including analyzing data submitted to the Commission and participating in
31 proceedings as provided in § 3–104 of this article.
32 (II) THE COMMISSION SHALL:

4 SENATE BILL 842
1 1. EACH FISCAL YEAR, SUBMIT THE COMMISSION’S
2 OPERATING PROGRAM BUDGET TO THE DEPARTMENT OF BUDGET AND
3 MANAGEMENT FOR INCLUSION IN THE STATE BUDGET BOOK FOR INFORMATIONAL
4 PURPOSES;
5 2. KEEP BUSINESS AND ACCOUNTING RECORDS USING
6 GENERALLY ACCEPTED ACCOUNTING PRINCIPLES; AND
7 3. AT THE END OF EACH FISCAL YEAR, HAVE AN
8 INDEPENDENT CERTIFIED PUBLIC ACCOUNTANT AUDIT THE ACCOUNTS AND
9 TRANSACTIONS OF THE COMMISSION.
10 (2) (i) As the Commission considers necessary, the Commission [shall
11 hire] MAY EMPLOY OR RETAIN AS INDEPENDENT CONTRACTORS, AND SET
12 COMPENSATION FOR, CONSULTANTS AND OTHER experts including economists, cost of
13 capital experts, rate design experts, accountants, engineers, transportation specialists,
14 [and] lawyers, FINANCIAL EXPERTS, MODELING EXPERTS, CLIMATE EXPERTS,
15 MANAGERS AND OTHER PROFESSIONAL PERSONNEL, AND ADMINISTRATIVE STAFF
16 AND PERSONNEL.
17 (ii) To assist in the regulation of intrastate hazardous liquid
18 pipelines under Title 11, Subtitle 2 of this article, the Commission shall include on its staff
19 at least one engineer who specializes in the storage of and the transportation of hazardous
20 liquid materials by pipeline.
21 (3) The Commission shall include on its staff one or more employees that
22 are experts in cybersecurity to:
23 (i) advise the Chairman of the Commission and the commissioners
24 on measures to improve oversight of the cybersecurity practices of public service companies;
25 (ii) consult with the Office of Security Management on cybersecurity
26 issues related to utility regulation;
27 (iii) assist the Commission in monitoring the minimum security
28 standards developed under § 5–306 of this article;
29 (iv) participate in briefings to discuss cybersecurity practices based
30 on:
31 1. applicable National Association of Regulatory Utility
32 Commissioners guidance; and

SENATE BILL 842 5
1 2. improvements to cybersecurity practices recommended in
2 the cybersecurity assessments required under § 5–306 of this article; and
3 (v) support public service companies that do not meet minimum
4 security standards with remediating vulnerabilities or addressing cybersecurity
5 assessment findings.
6 [(4) The Commission may retain on a case by case basis additional experts
7 as required for a particular matter.]
8 [(5)] (4) The lawyers who represent the Commission staff in proceedings
9 before the Commission shall be appointed by the Commission and shall be organized and
10 operate independently of the office of General Counsel.
11 [(6)] (5) (i) As required, the Commission shall hire public utility law
12 judges.
13 (ii) Public utility law judges are a separate organizational unit and
14 shall report directly to the Commission.
15 [(7)] (6) The Commission shall hire personal staff members for each
16 commissioner as required to provide advice, draft proposed orders and rulings, and perform
17 other personal staff functions.
18 [(8)] (7) (i) The Commission shall:
19 1. collaborate with the Office of Security Management to
20 establish cybersecurity standards and best practices for regulated entities, taking into
21 account utility needs and capabilities based on size;
22 2. periodically share information on cybersecurity initiatives
23 and best practices with municipal electric utilities; and
24 3. beginning on or before January 1, 2025, and every 2 years
25 thereafter:
26 A. collect certifications of a public service company’s
27 compliance with standards used in the assessments conducted under § 5–306 of this article
28 for cybersecurity–related policies and procedures; and
29 B. submit a report to the State Chief Information Security
30 Officer, or the Officer’s designee.
31 (ii) The report required under subparagraph (i) of this paragraph
32 shall include:

6 SENATE BILL 842
1 1. a general overview of cybersecurity technology and
2 policies used by public service companies in the State, grouped by the following types:
3 A. investor–owned electric companies;
4 B. electric cooperatives;
5 C. municipal electric companies;
6 D. gas companies; and
7 E. water companies;
8 2. general recommendations for improving cybersecurity
9 technology and policies used by public service companies in the State, grouped by the
10 following types:
11 A. investor–owned electric companies;
12 B. electric cooperatives;
13 C. municipal electric companies;
14 D. gas companies; and
15 E. water companies; and
16 3. for each certification collected:
17 A. the name of the public service company;
18 B. the date of the public service company’s most recent
19 cybersecurity assessment;
20 C. the cybersecurity framework used in the cybersecurity
21 assessment of the public service company; and
22 D. the name of the entity that completed the cybersecurity
23 assessment.
24 [(9)] (8) Subject to § 3–104 of this article, the Commission may delegate
25 to a commissioner or personnel the authority to perform an administrative function
26 necessary to carry out a duty of the Commission.
27 [(10) (i) Except as provided in subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph or
28 otherwise by law, all personnel of the Commission are subject to the provisions of the State
29 Personnel and Pensions Article.

