1 (ii) The following are in the executive service, management service,
2 or are special appointments in the State Personnel Management System:
3 1. each commissioner of the Commission;
4 2. the Executive Director;
5 3. the General Counsel and each assistant general counsel;
6 4. the Executive Secretary;
7 5. the commissioners’ personal staff members;
8 6. the chief public utility law judge; and
9 7. each license hearing officer.]
10 (e) (1) (I) THE COMMISSION SHALL ESTABLISH FOR THE EMPLOYEES
11 OF THE COMMISSION A PERSONNEL MANAGEMENT SYSTEM THAT OPERATES
12 INDEPENDENTLY OF THE STATE PERSONNEL MANAGEMENT SYSTEM.
13 (II) THE PERSONNEL MANAGEMENT SYSTEM ESTABLISHED BY
14 THE COMMISSION SHALL:
15 1. BE BASED ON MERIT; AND
16 2. INCLUDE FAIR AND EQUITABLE PROCEDURES FOR:
17 A. APPOINTING, HIRING, PROMOTING, TERMINATING,
18 AND REMOVING EMPLOYEES; AND
19 B. REDRESSING GRIEVANCES.
20 (2) ALL COMMISSION EMPLOYEES ARE SUBJECT TO DIVISIONS II
21 AND III OF THE STATE PERSONNEL AND PENSIONS ARTICLE.
22 [(1)] (3) The compensation of [the following personnel] ALL EMPLOYEES
23 shall be determined by the Commission and, if possible, in accordance with the State pay
24 plan[:
25 (1) the Executive Director;
26 (2) the General Counsel;

8 SENATE BILL 842
1 (3) the special appointment attorneys in the office of General Counsel;
2 (4) the Executive Secretary;
3 (5) the chief public utility law judge;
4 (6) each license hearing officer; and
5 (7) all Commission personnel in positions in:
6 (i) the management service; and
7 (ii) professional and technical classifications unique to the
8 Commission].
9 (4) ALL PERMANENT EMPLOYEES OF THE COMMISSION SHALL:
10 (I) BE CONSIDERED AS PERMANENT STATE EMPLOYEES FOR
11 THE PURPOSES OF TRANSFERRING TO OR FROM ANOTHER POSITION IN STATE
12 GOVERNMENT;
13 (II) RECEIVE CREDIT FOR SERVICE WITH THE COMMISSION FOR
14 ANY ACCRUED LEAVE AND BENEFITS; AND
15 (III) BE GRANTED THE SAME COMPENSATION CONSIDERATION
16 THAT WOULD BE PROVIDED TO AN EMPLOYEE TRANSFERRING WITHIN ANOTHER
17 DIVISION OF STATE GOVERNMENT.
18 (5) THE COMMISSION SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO GOVERN THE
19 PERSONNEL MANAGEMENT SYSTEM ADOPTED UNDER THIS SUBSECTION,
20 INCLUDING:
21 (I) PROCEDURES FOR APPOINTING, HIRING, PROMOTING,
22 TERMINATING, REMOVING, AND REINSTATING EMPLOYEES;
23 (II) POLICIES FOR LEAVE; AND
24 (III) PROCEDURES FOR HEARING AND REDRESSING GRIEVANCES
25 AND DISCIPLINARY ACTIONS.
26 [(f) (1) At least 45 days before the effective date of the change, the Commission
27 shall submit to the Secretary of Budget and Management each change to salary plans that
28 involves increases or decreases in salary ranges other than those associated with routine
29 reclassifications and promotions or general salary increases approved by the General
30 Assembly.

SENATE BILL 842 9
1 (2) Reportable changes include creation or abolition of classes, regrading
2 the classes from one established range to another, changes in salary guidelines to
3 administer the pay schedules, or creation of new pay schedules or ranges.
4 (3) The Secretary of Budget and Management shall:
5 (i) review the proposed changes; and
6 (ii) at least 15 days before the effective date of the proposed changes,
7 advise the Commission whether the changes would have an adverse effect on comparable
8 State jobs.
9 (4) Failure of the Secretary to respond in a timely manner is not considered
10 a statement of adverse effect.
11 (g) On or before January 31 of each year, the Commission shall report to the
12 Secretary of Budget and Management and, subject to § 2–1257 of the State Government
13 Article, to the General Assembly setting forth all personnel positions, classifications, and
14 salaries in the Commission as of the end of the preceding calendar year.]
15 (F) AT ANY TIME, THE COMMISSION MAY BE SUBJECT TO AN AUDIT AND
16 EXAMINATION OF ACCOUNTS AND TRANSACTIONS BY THE OFFICE OF LEGISLATIVE
17 AUDITS.
18 (G) THE COMMISSION IS EXEMPT FROM TAXATION BY THE STATE AND
19 LOCAL GOVERNMENT.
20 Article – State Finance and Procurement
21 11–203.
22 (C–1) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN TITLE 12, SUBTITLE 4 AND TITLE 14,
23 SUBTITLE 3 OF THIS ARTICLE, THIS DIVISION II DOES NOT APPLY TO THE PUBLIC
24 SERVICE COMMISSION.
25 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That all employees of the Public
26 Service Commission that are subject to the State Personnel Management System on the
27 effective date of this Act shall remain subject to the State Personnel Management System
28 until the Public Service Commission adopts a personnel management system that is
29 independent of the State Personnel Management System in accordance with § 2–108(e) of
30 the Public Utilities Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this Act.
31 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
32 1, 2026.

